      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A mother brings her newborn to the clinic, concerned about the baby&#39;s head, which appears enlarged and features visible veins. The physician, after evaluating the newborn, determines that the baby&#39;s condition is due to a disruption in cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) flow, leading to accumulation. While discussing the diagnosis and implications with the family, the mother&#39;s sister inquires about normal CSF production in a child. What is the normal rate of CSF production in a child?</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2023/04/30/9_vxVMydq.jpg\" style=\"height:182px; width:295px\" /></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q4350943",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32797,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) 20 mL/hr</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The normal rate of CSF production in a child is approximately <strong>20 mL/hr</strong>. CSF is produced by the<strong> choroid plexuses </strong>located in the <strong>ventricles of the brain </strong>and the rate remains <strong>relatively constant</strong>. This production leads to a total turnover of CSF about three to four times per day in both children and adults.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The normal production of CSF in an infant is 20 mL/hr.</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Overproduction or under excretion</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">, resulting from an obstruction in the CSF flow pathway will result in <strong>Hydrocephalus.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: OP Ghai 9th Edition, Page No-578. </span></span></strong></p>",
