          "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Non obstructive </span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">hydrocephalus</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 53032,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Both A and C</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 5-year-old child is brought to the hospital by his mother due to symptoms of headache, fever, neck rigidity, and photophobia. Meningitis is diagnosed, and the child is admitted for treatment. Five days into the hospital stay, the child&#39;s head begins to enlarge, a sign indicative of developing hydrocephalus. This is suspected to be a secondary complication of the meningitis. What is the most common type of hydrocephalus observed in children as a post-meningitis complication?</span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2367369",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 32798,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D) Both A and C.</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Communicating hydrocephalus</strong>, also known as <strong>non-obstructive hydrocephalus, </strong>is the most common type following <strong>meningitis in children. </strong>This type occurs when the<strong> flow of CSF is blocked </strong>after it <strong>exits the ventricles</strong>. This is often due to <strong>scarring and blockage of the CSF reabsorption pathways</strong>, such as the <strong>arachnoid villi</strong>, by the inflammatory process of meningitis. The term <strong>&#39;communicating&#39; </strong>is used because the<strong> CSF can still flow between the ventricles, </strong>which remain open and &#39;communicate&#39; with each other.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\">&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. Non-communicating hydrocephalus, </span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">or obstructive hydrocephalus, occurs when there is a <strong>blockage in the ventricular system </strong>itself, which is less common following meningitis. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>MC type </strong>of hydrocephalus in children with meningitis is<strong> Communicating hydrocephalus/ Non obstructive hydrocephalus</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>MC </strong>cause of<strong> non-communicating hydrocephalus </strong>is <strong>stenosis </strong>of the <strong>aqueductal canal of sylvius </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: OP Ghai 9th Edition, Page No-578. </span></span></strong></p>",
